{{refimprove|date=September 2008}} {{italics title}} <!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:"Woman with bicycle" by Knox Martin.jpg|right|thumb|150px]] --> '''''Woman with Bicycle''''' is a six-story [[Mural|wall painting]] created by the [[United States|American]] [[Painting|painter]], [[sculptor]] and [[muralist]] [[Knox Martin]] in 1979 under the sponsorship of the [[Public Art Fund]].
==Former Landmark== A well-known [[New York City]] art landmark, ''Woman with Bicycle'' was located at [[Houston Street|Houston]] and [[MacDougal Street|MacDougal]] Streets in [[Manhattan]]. Vivian Raynor of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote in 1981 of Knox Martin and ''Woman with Bicycle'':
{{Quote|text=The artist is best known for his repertory of signs and symbols that allude to nature and, in particular, to the female form. Flatly and freely painted in Pop colors, they have often been executed on a grand scale, as in the outdoor mural at West Houston and MacDougal Streets in Manhattan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/06/30/nyregion/art-knox-martin-angry-but-more-human.html|title=ART; KNOX MARTIN: ANGRY BUT MORE HUMAN|last=Raynor|first=Vivien|date=1981-06-30|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-04-16|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>|sign=Vivian Raynor, ''The New York Times''|source=}}
In 2002, ''Woman with Bicycle'' was covered over with an underwear ad.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}}
